    "summary": "The First Intermediate Period of Egypt, approximately 2181–2055 BC, was a time of political fragmentation and decentralisation following the collapse of the [[event:41|Old Kingdom]]. With the weakening of the central government at Memphis after the [[event:1715|Sixth Dynasty]], Egypt fractured into competing regional power centres. The Seventh and Eighth Dynasties at Memphis were brief and largely ineffective, while the Ninth and Tenth Dynasties ruled from Herakleopolis in Middle Egypt and competed with the Eleventh Dynasty based at Thebes in Upper Egypt.\n\nThe period was marked by social upheaval, agricultural disruption, and significant cultural change. Literary texts from the period — such as the Admonitions of Ipuwer and the Lamentations of Khakheperre-Sonb — describe social inversion, with nobles reduced to poverty and commoners rising to prominence. While these texts may be rhetorical in nature, they reflect genuine anxiety about the breakdown of the cosmic and social order that the pharaoh was meant to uphold. Climate deterioration linked to the [[event:1795|4.2 Kiloyear Event]] likely reduced Nile flood levels and contributed to food shortages.\n\nDespite the political fragmentation, the First Intermediate Period saw important cultural developments. The democratisation of funerary practices, including the spread of coffin texts previously reserved for royalty, suggests that the collapse of central authority created space for wider social participation in religion. Provincial art styles flourished, and local traditions that had been subordinated to the canonical Memphis style gained expression. The period ended when the Theban Eleventh Dynasty, under Mentuhotep II, reunified Egypt around 2055 BC, inaugurating [[event:51|the Middle Kingdom]].",
